description.value: One artefact and 5 beads in different shapes and materials.  A: Conical artefact made of red carnelian, with a flat base and a pointed top, broken off at the end, possibly when the perforation was started. Well finished. The thinner end has several flattened areas from the rough shaping. Possibly a gaming-figure. B: Spacer-bead made of light turquoise faience, two and a half segments preserved, good quality. C: Small remains of a cylindrical segmented bead with a very small diameter. Two segments preserved. D: Very short cylindrical bead made of a light blue faience. E: Elongated spherical bead made of faience with faint traces of a light blue glaze. F: Disc-shaped bead made of ostrich eggshell.

description.value: Clay figure made of a brown fine clay that was lightly fired and consolidated after excavation resulting in a darker surface colour. The object itself is very crudely formed, roughly horizontally cylindrical with slightly pointed ends. One end has been pinched together and curls slightly upwards. From the other end another piece would have been run off but is broken off. A small, horizontal slit appears on one side, its outer end was formed out of the main body part still showing three small (children) finger impressions on each side of the slit. The slit itself measures 1.05 x 0.2 cm and has a depth of about 2.2 cm, maybe another (part of an) object was attached here. The object could have been a stylized animal figurine.

A small hole appears in the top with a width of 0.25-0.35 cm and a depth of 1.8 cm. The object is roughly shaped and finished, and shows finger impressions from shaping it. The function is not clear as it is to small for a container like AW386, and is not flat at the "bottom". Attachment of another clay object or a stick? The object card shows that originally two objects of this kind have been found. The location of 413B is unknown but this object was more drop-shaped and also had a hole.

description.value: Incised limestone block: this slightly irregular rectangular block is incised on all surfaces with hieroglyphic texts. Along the sides are two dedications to Ptah on behalf of the workman Wennekhu and Hormin. On the upper surface there is a vertical line of text with the name of the workman 'Imn-m-w??, and on the lower surface is written the name of the outline-draughtsman P?-R?-?tp. The block is in good condition apart from slight damage to the bottom text. Considerable traces of red paint remain on the lines bordering the inscriptions. Traces of blue paint can be seen in some of the signs and white paint on the body of the block.
